Fs%2Fwww.bbc.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fworld-latin-america-67597566.amp%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bbc.co.uk%2Fnews%2Fworld-latin-america-67597566.amp%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22How%20Emmanuel%20Le%20Roy%20Ladurie's%20Accounts%20of%20Europe%E2%80%99s%20Peoples%20Broke%20New%20Ground%20in%20History%20Writing%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01195435%2FLadurie.jpg%5C%22%3E%3Cp%3EEmmanuel%20Le%20Roy%20Ladurie%2C%20who%20died%20on%20November%2022%2C%202023%2C%20was%20a%20part%20of%20the%20Annales%20school%20or%20group%20of%20historians.%20But%20in%20some%20ways%2C%20especially%20in%20his%20later%20writings%2C%20he%20stepped%20outside%20the%20trend%20of%20history%20writing%20that%20the%20historians%20of%20the%20Annales%20school%20had%20established.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20school%20derived%20its%20name%20from%20the%20journal%20%3Cem%3EAnnales%3A%20economies%2C%20societes%2C%20civilisations%3C%2Fem%3E%20started%20by%20two%20outstanding%20French%20historians%2C%20Marc%20Bloch%20(1886-1944%2C%20shot%20by%20the%20Nazis%20for%20being%20part%20of%20the%20French%20Resistance)%20and%20Lucien%20Febvre%20(1878-1956).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20purpose%20of%20the%20journal%2C%20as%20its%20name%20suggests%2C%20was%20to%20attempt%20to%20portray%20a%20kind%20of%20%E2%80%9Ctotal%20history%E2%80%9D%20which%20would%20encompass%20all%20the%20facets%20of%20human%20life.%20As%20Bloch%20wrote%20in%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Historian%E2%80%99s%20Craft%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%E2%80%9Cwherever%20he%20%5Bthe%20historian%5D%20catches%20the%20scent%20of%20human%20flesh%2C%20there%20his%20quarry%20lies.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20other%20feature%20was%20to%20look%20at%20history%20over%20a%20long%20period%2C%20not%20through%20episodic%20bursts%20%E2%80%93%20the%20%3Cem%3Elo%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cem%3Engue%20dur%C3%A9%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cem%3Ee%3C%2Fem%3E%20as%20it%20was%20called.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBloch%20tried%20to%20capture%20this%20in%20his%20masterpiece%20%3Cem%3EFeudal%20Society%3C%2Fem%3E%20(English%20translation%201961%2C%20written%20in%20French%20probably%20in%20the%20closing%20years%20of%20the%201930s%2C%20before%20Bloch%20went%20underground%20to%20work%20for%20the%20Resistance)%2C%20which%20looked%20at%20the%20evolution%20and%20structure%20of%20feudal%20society%20over%20a%20span%20of%20nearly%20four%20centuries.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20question%20that%20Bloch%20posed%20was%20the%20following%20(in%20his%20own%20words)%3A%20%E2%80%9CWhat%20are%20the%20distinctive%20features%20of%20this%20portion%20of%20the%20past%20which%20have%20given%20it%20a%20claim%20to%20be%20treated%20in%20isolation%3F%20In%20other%20words%2C%20what%20we%20are%20attempting%20here%20is%20to%20analyse%20and%20explain%20a%20social%20structure%20and%20its%20unifying%20principles.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHe%20was%20thus%20not%20concerned%20with%20the%20actions%20of%20kings%2C%20princes%2C%20knights%20and%20so%20on%20but%20was%20trying%20to%20venture%20into%20a%20form%20of%20history%20writing%20that%20was%20based%20on%20the%20%E2%80%9Cobservation%20of%20social%20phenomena.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBloch%20and%20his%20followers%20in%20the%20Annales%20school%20were%20thus%20not%20undermining%20empiricism%20(note%20the%20use%20of%20the%20word%20%E2%80%9Cobservation%E2%80%9D)%2C%20which%20was%20the%20staple%20of%20history%20writing%20in%20Germany%20and%20Britain.%20Rather%2C%20he%20was%20shifting%20the%20object%20of%20observation%20from%20%E2%80%9Cpolitics%E2%80%9D%20to%20society%20(in%20the%20broadest%20sense%20of%20the%20word).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOne%20consequence%20of%20this%20was%20the%20marginalisation%20of%20the%20individual%20%E2%80%93%20Bloch%20did%20not%20look%20at%20the%20action%20of%20any%20one%20individual%2C%20however%20important%20and%20pre-eminent.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHuman%20beings%20were%20not%20absent%20from%20his%20analysis%3A%20they%20were%20present%2C%20very%20much%20present%2C%20but%20as%20an%20anonymous%20collective.%20Bloch%20even%20delved%20into%20the%20modes%20of%20thought%20and%20feeling%3A%20this%20later%20came%20to%20be%20dubbed%20as%20the%20history%20of%20%3Cem%3Ementalit%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cem%3E%C3%A9%3C%2Fem%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20works%20of%20French%20historian%20Fernand%20Braudel%2C%20the%20disappearance%20of%20the%20individual%20was%20almost%20complete.%20Individuals%20had%20no%20agency%3B%20they%20were%20the%20products%20of%20the%20historical%20circumstances%20in%20which%20they%20found%20themselves.%20The%20historians%E2%80%99%20job%20was%20to%20explain%20those%20circumstances.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHe%20was%20to%20write%20famously%20in%20his%20magnum%20opus%2C%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Mediterranean%20and%20the%20Mediterranean%20World%20in%20the%20Age%20of%20Philip%20II%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%E2%80%9CWhen%20I%20think%20of%20the%20individual%20I%20am%20always%20inclined%20to%20see%20him%20imprisoned%20within%20a%20destiny%20in%20which%20he%20himself%20has%20little%20hand.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBraudel%20was%2C%20in%20a%20different%20way%2C%20echoing%20and%20with%20greater%20emphasis%20the%20views%20of%20Marx%20as%20articulated%20in%20that%20famous%20opening%20paragraph%20of%20%3Cem%3EThe%2018%3Csup%3Eth%3C%2Fsup%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cem%3E%20Brumaire%20of%20Louis%20Bonaparte%3C%2Fem%3E%3A%20%E2%80%9CMen%20make%20their%20own%20history%20but%20they%20do%20not%20make%20it%20just%20as%20they%20please.%20The%20dead%20hand%20of%20the%20past%20hangs%20over%20their%20present%20activities.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20issue%20that%20Braudel%20and%20Marx%20were%20raising%20is%20the%20one%20of%20human%20agency%2C%20or%20rather%2C%20the%20absence%20of%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%E2%80%99s%20early%20work%2C%20especially%20%3Cem%3ETimes%20of%20Feast%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%3Cem%3E%20Times%20of%20Famine%3A%20A%20History%20of%20Climate%20Since%20the%20Year%201000%3C%2Fem%3E%20(first%20published%20in%20English%20in%201971%20but%20in%20French%20in%201967)%2C%20was%20an%20example%20of%20history%20not%20only%20in%20the%20%3Cem%3Elongue%3C%2Fem%3E%20%3Cem%3Edur%C3%A9%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cem%3Ee%20%3C%2Fem%3Ebut%20also%20history%20bereft%20human%20choice%20and%20agency.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20book%20that%20made%20Ladurie%20well%20known%20was%20%3Cem%3EThe%20Peasants%20of%20Languedoc%3C%2Fem%3E.%20This%20was%20his%20doctoral%20dissertation%2C%20which%20was%20published%20in%20France%20in%201966%20and%20then%20translated%20into%20English%20in%201974.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%20looked%20at%20the%20history%20of%20agriculture%20over%20three%20centuries%20through%20the%20prism%20of%20quantitative%20data%20%E2%80%93%20levels%20of%20productivity%2C%20wages%2C%20rents%2C%20profits%20and%20so%20on.%20He%20arrived%20at%20the%20conclusion%20that%20for%20the%20peasants%20of%20Languedoc%2C%20nothing%20had%20changed%20over%20300%20years%3B%20they%20were%20so%20rooted%20in%20their%20own%20culture%20and%20practices%20that%20they%20were%20averse%20to%20innovation%20and%20change.%20Agrarian%20life%20in%20Languedoc%2C%20Ladurie%20argued%2C%20had%20remained%20frozen%20and%20immobile.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01200751%2FLanguedoc.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221000%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01200751%2FLanguedoc.jpg%201000w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01200751%2FLanguedoc-300x168.jpg%20300w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-687325%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22560%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3ELadurie%20went%20on%20to%20say%20that%20the%20the%20rural%20world%20of%20Languedoc%20%E2%80%9Chad%20not%20yet%20suffered%20the%20attacks%20of%20rationalism%3B%20it%20still%20had%20a%20taste%20for%20the%20magical%20and%20the%20marvellous.%E2%80%9D%20Photo%3A%20Mick%20Stephenson%2FWikimedia%20Commons.%20CC%20BY%20SA%203.0%20Unported.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20phenomenon%20of%20immobility%20seems%20to%20have%20been%20a%20pre-modern%20French%20predicament.%20Emma%20Rothschild%20in%20her%20book%20%3Cem%3EAn%20Infinite%20History%3C%2Fem%3E%20notes%20that%20Balzac%20in%20his%20novels%2C%20written%20in%20the%2019th%20century%2C%20described%20the%20society%20of%20Angoul%C3%AAme%20(a%20small%20town%20in%20south%20west%20France)%20as%20being%20marked%20by%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20most%20fatal%20immobility%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThrough%20his%20emphasis%20on%20the%20absence%20of%20change%2C%20Ladurie%20was%20also%20going%20against%20one%20of%20the%20prevailing%20ideas%20of%20Marxist%20historiography%2C%20i.e.%2C%20that%20agrarian%20change%20was%20producing%20a%20land%20market%2C%20higher%20rents%20and%20profits%20and%20the%20dispossession%20of%20peasants%20%E2%80%93%20the%20process%20of%20primitive%20accumulation%20as%20Marx%20called%20it%20in%20%3Cem%3ECapital%3C%2Fem%3E%20volume%201%20%E2%80%93%20and%20thus%20paving%20the%20way%20for%20the%20emergence%20of%20capitalism.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESuch%20a%20process%20may%20have%20occurred%20in%20England%20but%20certainly%20not%20in%20Languedoc%2C%20shackled%20as%20the%20peasants%20of%20the%20region%20were%20to%20the%20absence%20of%20change.%20Economic%20change%20and%20the%20absence%20of%20it%20could%20not%20always%20be%20analysed%20in%20terms%20of%20economic%20factors%3A%20culture%20had%20a%20vital%20role%20and%20that%20culture%20needed%20to%20be%20understood.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%20had%20thus%20turned%20the%20then-prevalent%20Marxist%20base-superstructure%20analogy%20on%20its%20head.%20Much%20as%20Marx%20had%20turned%20Hegel%20on%20his%20head.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%20returned%20to%20Languedoc%20in%20%3Cem%3ELove%2C%20Death%20and%20Money%20in%20the%20Pays%20d%E2%80%99Oc%3C%2Fem%3E%20(first%20published%20in%20French%201980%2C%20English%20translation%20in%201982).%20This%20time%20he%20looked%20at%20culture%2C%20emotions%2C%20folklore%20%E2%80%93%20aspects%20of%20social%20life%20that%20historians%20often%20ignored.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20this%20book%2C%20Ladurie%20took%20a%20novel%2C%20%3Cem%3EJean-L%E2%80%99Ont-Pris%3C%2Fem%3E%20by%20Jean%20Baptiste%20Castor%20Fabre%20(1727-83)%2C%20which%20was%20considered%20a%20masterpiece%20and%20as%20a%20realistic%20depiction%20of%20rural%20life%20in%2018th%20century%20Languedoc%2C%20and%20contrasted%20this%20with%20the%20culture%20of%20the%20region%20in%20the%20%3Cem%3Eancien%20r%C3%A9gime%3C%2Fem%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHe%20considered%20the%20novel%20%E2%80%9Cin%20terms%20of%20folk%20literature%20%E2%80%A6%20%5Bto%5D%20get%20a%20clearer%20idea%20of%20the%20extent%20to%20which%20%3Cem%3EJean-L%E2%80%99Ont-Pris%3C%2Fem%3E%20is%20a%20realistic%20description%20of%20village%20life.%E2%80%9D%20He%20was%20thus%20looking%20at%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20thick%20file%20concerning%20the%20relations%20between%20literature%20and%20history%2C%20fiction%20and%20fact.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%E2%80%99s%20analysis%20emphasised%20that%20the%20mentality%20of%20the%20rural%20world%20of%20Languedoc%20%E2%80%9Chad%20not%20yet%20suffered%20the%20attacks%20of%20rationalism%3B%20it%20still%20had%20a%20taste%20for%20the%20magical%20and%20the%20marvellous.%E2%80%9D%20He%20revealed%20what%20he%20called%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20infraculture%20of%20the%20Enlightenment%3A%20a%20ground%20floor%2C%20occupied%20by%20the%20dialect%20writers%20of%20the%20provinces%3B%20and%20a%20basement%2C%20crossed%2C%20as%20if%20by%20cables%2C%20by%20the%20oral%20networks%20of%20folk-tale%20transmission.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%E2%80%99s%20%3Cem%3EMontaillou%3A%20Cathars%20and%20Catholics%20in%20a%20French%20Village%2C%201494-1324%3C%2Fem%3E%20(published%20in%20French%20in%201978%3B%20English%20translation%20the%20same%20year)%20became%20a%20bestseller.%20This%20popularity%20is%20somewhat%20inexplicable%20because%20the%20book%2C%20based%20on%20solid%20archival%20research%2C%20was%20by%20no%20means%20written%20for%20a%20popular%20readership.%20The%20only%20plausible%20explanation%20seems%20to%20be%20the%20universal%20love%20for%20a%20good%20story%20peopled%20with%20unforgettable%20characters.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01201357%2F1077px-Montaillou_village.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221077%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01201357%2F1077px-Montaillou_village.jpg%201077w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01201357%2F1077px-Montaillou_village-300x200.jpg%20300w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01201357%2F1077px-Montaillou_village-1024x685.jpg%201024w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-687326%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22720%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EMontaillou%20is%20a%20tiny%20village%20in%20the%20Pyrenees%20at%20the%20cusp%20of%20France%20and%20Spain%20and%20adjoining%20Languedoc.%20Photo%3A%20Xfigpower%2FWikimedia%20Commons.%20CC%20BY%20SA%203.0.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFor%20students%20of%20history%2C%20%3Cem%3EMontaillou%3C%2Fem%3E%20offered%20the%20first%20glimpse%20that%20Ladurie%20was%20evolving%20beyond%20the%20Annales%20school.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFor%20one%20thing%2C%20he%20was%2C%20in%20this%20book%2C%20not%20concerned%20with%20the%20%3Cem%3Elongue%20dur%C3%A9%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cem%3Ee%3C%2Fem%3E%3A%20the%20time%20span%20was%20a%20mere%20thirty%20years.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFor%20another%2C%20there%20were%20individuals%20in%20the%20book%3A%20identified%20by%20name%20and%20occupation%3B%20individuals%20who%20made%20choices%2C%20who%20loved%2C%20married%2C%20lied%20and%20committed%20other%20transgressions.%20Individuals%20who%20were%20vulnerable.%20The%20cast%20of%20characters%2C%20as%20Hugh%20Trevor-Roper%20noted%20in%20a%20review%20of%20the%20book%2C%20was%20memorably%20Chaucerian.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHere%20was%20history%20that%20was%20not%20driven%20by%20vast%20impersonal%20forces%20but%20by%20human%20agency%2C%20human%20beliefs%20and%20authority%20wielded%20by%20human%20beings.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20story%20of%20Montaillou%20%E2%80%93%20a%20tiny%20village%20in%20the%20Pyrenees%20at%20the%20cusp%20of%20France%20and%20Spain%20and%20adjoining%20Languedoc%2C%20the%20district%20that%20Ladurie%20knew%20so%20well%20%E2%80%93%20was%20reconstructed%20from%20the%20archives%20of%20the%20Inquisition.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Inquisition%20in%20the%20village%20was%20carried%20out%20by%20a%20bishop%2C%20Jacques%20Fournier%2C%20who%20was%20later%20to%20become%20Pope%20at%20Avignon%20under%20the%20name%20of%20Benedict%20XII.%20Detailed%20records%20were%20kept%20of%20these%20interrogations%20and%20from%20these%20it%20is%20possible%20to%20get%20direct%20testimony%20of%20the%20peasants%20themselves.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EMontaillou%20was%20the%20last%20village%20which%20subscribed%20to%20and%20supported%20what%20the%20orthodox%20Christian%20church%20in%20Rome%20labelled%20and%20condemned%20as%20the%20Cathar%20or%20the%20Albigensian%20heresy.%20The%20heretics%20were%20the%20victims%20of%20the%20savage%20Albigensian%20crusade%20in%20which%20knights%20did%20not%20travel%20to%20the%20Holy%20Land%20to%20fight%20the%20Muslims%20but%20descended%20on%20tiny%20European%20villages%20to%20suppress%20dissent%20and%20unorthodoxy%20in%20the%20name%20of%20the%20Lord.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%20told%20this%20story%20in%20great%20detail%20captured%20with%20poignancy%20and%20with%20an%20enviable%20mastery%20over%20the%20documents.%20He%20transported%20readers%20back%20in%20time.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIf%20in%20%3Cem%3EMontaillou%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20Ladurie%20had%20moved%20from%20the%20long%20span%20of%20history%20to%20thirty%20years%2C%20in%20%3Cem%3ECarnival%3A%20A%20People%E2%80%99s%20Uprising%20at%20Romans%201579-1580%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20(published%20in%20French%201979%20and%20in%20English%20the%20next%20year)%20he%20focussed%20on%20one%20episode%20lasting%20a%20few%20weeks.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01202506%2F900px-Marseille-carnival-sun-and-moon.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22900%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01202506%2F900px-Marseille-carnival-sun-and-moon.jpg%20900w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01202506%2F900px-Marseille-carnival-sun-and-moon-300x240.jpg%20300w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-687328%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22720%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EA%20modern-day%20Mardi%20Gras%20carnival.%20Photo%3A%20Say-Mars-Say-Yeah%2FWikimedia%20Commons.%20CC%20BY%203.0.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ERomans%20was%20a%20textile%20centre%20located%20to%20the%20southeast%20of%20Lyons.%20Every%20year%20in%20February%2C%20Romans%20was%20the%20site%20of%20a%20Mardi%20Gras%20carnival%20%E2%80%93%20festivities%20to%20mark%20the%20rite%20of%20passage%20from%20winter%20to%20spring.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%201580%2C%20the%20colourful%20carnival%20carried%20the%20stains%20of%20blood%20as%20the%20celebrations%20morphed%20into%20a%20massacre%20in%20which%20the%20nobility%20and%20the%20notables%20of%20the%20town%20were%20either%20killed%20or%20imprisoned%20by%20the%20common%20people%2C%20who%20were%20protesting%20against%20the%20tax%20exactions%20and%20privileges%20enjoyed%20by%20those%20belonging%20to%20the%20upper%20echelons%20of%20Romans%E2%80%99%20society.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%20reconstructed%20the%20carnival%20in%20detail%20and%20contextualised%20it%20in%20terms%20of%20carnival%20behaviour%20drawing%20on%20the%20findings%20of%20anthropologists.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20carnival%2C%20as%20is%20well%20known%2C%20was%20an%20occasion%20when%20the%20traditional%20hierarchies%20of%20society%20were%20turned%20upside%20down.%20It%20was%20also%20an%20occasion%20for%20the%20gathering%20of%20a%20large%20number%20of%20people%20with%20parades%20and%20masquerades.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20winter%20of%201580%2C%20a%20seemingly%20innocent%20episode%20acquired%20a%20radically%20different%20and%20violent%20dimension.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%20was%20at%20his%20dazzling%20best%20here%2C%20displaying%20his%20insights%20into%20rural%20life%20and%20culture%2C%20his%20reading%20of%20folklore%20and%20his%20ability%20to%20draw%20from%20different%20disciplines.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20books%20presented%20here%20in%20outline%20were%20of%20course%20not%20the%20only%20ones%20that%20Ladurie%20had%20written%20in%20his%20long%20career%20as%20a%20historian.%20I%20have%20deliberately%20chosen%20the%20texts%20that%20help%20to%20track%20a%20certain%20trajectory%20%E2%80%93%20beginning%20with%20the%20Annales%20mode%20of%20writing%20history%20to%20a%20richer%20approach%20in%20which%20human%20beings%20came%20alive.%20Ladurie%20excelled%20in%20both%20modes%20of%20writing%20history.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EPostscript%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELadurie%20was%20a%20member%20of%20the%20French%20Communist%20Party%2C%20which%20he%20left%20when%20the%20Soviet%20Union%20invaded%20Hungary%20in%201956.%20Coincidentally%2C%20he%20thus%20joined%20a%20select%20group%20of%20top-class%20historians%20who%20had%20also%20resigned%20from%20communist%20parties%20of%20their%20own%20countries%20%E2%80%93%20Christopher%20Hill%2C%20E.P.%20Thompson%2C%20Rodney%20Hilton%2C%20Dorothy%20Thompson%20(in%20Britain)%20and%20Ranajit%20Guha%20(in%20India).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESomething%20more%20than%20the%20historian%E2%80%99s%20craft%20had%20made%20these%20great%20historians%20take%20such%20a%20life-changing%20decision.%20I%20suppose%20one%20could%20call%20it%20their%20humanity%20%E2%80%93%20the%20same%20sentiment%20that%20had%20drawn%20Marc%20Bloch%20to%20the%20Resistance.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22http%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fauthor%2Frudrangshu-mukherjee%5C%22%3ERudrangshu%20Mukherjee%3C%2Fa%3E%20is%20chancellor%20and%20professor%20of%20history%20at%20Ashoka%20University.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1701493572000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F12%2F01195435%2FLadurie.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fremembering-emmanuel-le-roy-ladurie%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Ladurie%20was%20part%20of%20the%20influential%20Annales%20school%20of%20historians%20but%20also%20grew%20beyond%20it.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A3%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fhistory%2Fremembering-emmanuel-le-roy-ladurie%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22On%20COP28%20sidelines%2C%20philanthropies%20invest%20%24450%20million%20to%20help%20tackle%20methane%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%22%2C%22published%22%3A1701493445000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fstatic.toiimg.com%2Fphoto%2Fmsid-105671876%2Cimgsize-126256.cms%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Ftimesofindia.indiatimes.com%2Fon-cop28-sidelines-philanthropies-invest-450-million-to-help-tackle-methane%2Farticleshow%2F105671715.cms%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22%3Cimg%20border%3D%5C%220%5C%22%20align%3D%5C%22left%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftimesofindia.indiatimes.com%2Fphoto%2F105671715.cms%5C%22%20hspace%3D%5C%2210%5C%22%3EDeep-pocketed%20philanthropies%2C%20including%20Bezos%20Earth%20Fund%2C%20Bloomberg%20Philanthropies%2C%20and%20Se